@walkert That is something that I cannot accept in the current state of Jedi. If you're doing this without proper checks, you're actually making it easy for segfaults. Compiled (binary) files in a virtualenv can easily cause one - even with normal packages like `PyQt4`.

The same reason caused me to reject #539. It's not like I wouldn't want a version agnostic Jedi, but helping segfaults to work is definitely not what I want either.

I guess we have to move the whole import/compiled logic of Jedi into a separate `multiprocessing` process. That would solve our issues and we could easily just restart it if it segfaults. By doing that, we could maybe also include @blueyed's plan to include other library versions. This would also make Jedi more secure in general. There wouldn't be a reason anymore for Jedi to stop working (which it could do now with home made invalid compiled files that cause segfaults).

```
$ cat /tmp/3.c
typedef void (*f)(void *data);
typedef void (*f)(void *data);
```

This file parses just fine in pycparser 2.18; So I guess I'm not sure what cffi is doing here with the different calls.

@newville Things to consider:

1. [Matlab](https://www.mathworks.com/help/matlab/ref/acosd.html?requestedDomain=www.mathworks.com), [Octave](https://www.gnu.org/software/octave/doc/v4.0.1/Trigonometry.html#XREFacosd), & [Scilab](https://help.scilab.org/docs/6.0.0/en_US/acosd.html) feature these functions, so the syntax should probably be `acosd()` to follow their convention.  The appended "d" seems intuitive.  It is convenient and concise to have dedicated degree-trig functions; asteval may be more likely to be employed in applied mathematics and engineering use-cases, where degree units are more common, than other python use-cases.
2. Probably should be added from both `math` & `numpy`; Is one a fallback for the other?

