@ulzha 

> -Building images is usually part of deployment process

I think the key word here is "usually". What I am hoping to achieve for batch jobs in general is that each would come up in a container (based on some standard image or set of images) with the job invocation as the CMD, so that the container would stop itself once the job ended. I can see doing this now for a Luigi workflow (in fact, I am very close to doing this now already, and I know many already do). What I think a Luigi docker task would offer is the ability to do the same sort of thing at the individual Task level, and have all of Luigi's strengths in managing that containerized dependencies, as we enjoy having it do for any other sort of task. Each containerized Task might itself invoke a `luigi` command line job, or (of course) any other sort of desired processing from outside Luigi, including programs in other languages. I suppose even the sort of thing I'm describing now could already be done, using `docker-py` and some logic in a run() call, but like @tjamet said at the beginning, it seems like it would be nice to have a `contrib` module to handle that in a standard, idiomatically Luigi-ish way, so we don't all each have to roll our own.

