Re: reentrant code: No, I don't think there's any way we can make that work.  If some other code calls something that is going to effect a change in the value the python class method returns, I can' see any way that we can know about it.  That's a limitation, to be sure, but I think it's one we'll have to be content with documenting as a limitation (until/unless someone can come up with a way to work around it).

There's also a limitation in code that expects to be able to usefully modify non-`const` references, e.g.

```C++
Class A {
    int _v;
public:
    virtual int& v();
}
// ...
A a;
a.v() = 4;
```
That's only going to update the cache value, of course, but I can't see that's there anything we can do about it (aside from documenting it as a limitation).

