I agree that we should have some sort of abstraction to allow for common re-use of, for example, cells. But this proposal seems to also be trying to serve double-duty as replacing--for control flow ops--the graph body *itself* with the Function abstraction. If I understand correctly, this proposal provides no provision for accessing implicitly live values in an enclosing scope.  Note the below:

`
bool foobar = false;
int baz = 3;
for (int i=0; i<100; ++i) {
  bool abcd = !foobar; // Note I can access this due to lexical scoping
  if (baz < 10) {
    baz++;
  }
}
`

Note that we have well-defined semantics for lexical scoping in this code example and in the control flow proposal. This is possible because the blocks are defined within the context of their parent scope(s). Note that if we were to convert all of these control structure bodies to functions, we would need to explicitly mark all live-in and live-out values:

`
bool foobar = false;
int baz = 3;
for (int i=0; i<100; ++i) baz = for_loop_body(i, foobar, baz)

int conditional_body(baz) {
  return baz+1;
}

int for_loop_body(int i, bool foobar, int baz) {
  bool abcd = !foobar;
  return conditional_body(baz);
}
`

Our proposal is that a function can be *invoked* from a lexically-scoped subgraph, but the subgraph itself should not be conflated with this function abstraction. To do otherwise would unnecessarily complicate serialized models with (sometimes nested!) control structures.

Concretely, let's take a look at LSTM cells, in pseudo-deep-learning-C:

`
Tensor iW_f, iW_i, iW_o, iW_c;
Tensor hW_f, hW_i, hW_o, hW_g;
Tensor b_f, b_i, b_o, b_g

Tensor hidden_state_carried_dep;
Tensor cell_state_carried_dep;

vector<Tensor> y;
vector<Tensor> x;

// Assume * is overloaded as matmul, . is overloaded as Hadamard product
for (int i=0; i<seqlen; ++i) {
  Tensor f_t = sigmoid(iW_f * x[t] + hW_f * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_f);
  Tensor i_t = sigmoid(iW_i * x[t] + hW_i * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_i);
  Tensor o_t = sigmoid(iW_o * x[t] + hW_o * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_o);
  Tensor c_t = f_t . cell_state_carried_dep + i_t . sigmoid(iW_c*x[t] + hW_c * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_c);
  Tensor h_t = o_t . sigmoid(c_t);
  hidden_state_carried_dep = h_t;
  cell_state_carried_dep = c_t;
  y[i] = h_t;
}
`

The inputs to this code block are as follows: iW_f, iW_i, iW_o, iW_c, hW_f, hW_i, hW_o, hW_g, b_f, b_i, b_o, b_g, x.
The loop carried deps (count as both input and output) are: hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep.
The outputs are: y.

So now I have a function signature that looks like:

`
y, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep = for_loop_body(iW_f, iW_i, iW_o, iW_c, hW_f, hW_i, hW_o, hW_g, b_f, b_i, b_o, b_g, x, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep)
`

One could argue you could fuse together the weight and bias matrices, but this has performance implications depending on backend and batch size. I think it's another interesting discussion about optimization opportunities with either representation and the trade-offs between expressibility in the IR vs expressibility in the frontend and semantics provided to optimizers. But ignoring the implications let's reformulate this as fused:

`
y, hidden_state_carried_deps, cell_state_carried_dep = for_loop_body(iW, hW, b, x, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep)
`

But this still becomes unnecessarily cumbersome when you want to compose this into a broader loop body, for example implementing Multiplicative Integration LSTM (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.06630.pdf). Say we have a standard LSTM cell with the following signature (affine layers factored out due to the nature of MI-lstm):

`y, hidden_state_carried_deps, cell_state_carried_dep = LSTMCell(gates, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep)
`

Then we write:

`
Tensor iW_f, iW_i, iW_o, iW_c;
Tensor hW_f, hW_i, hW_o, hW_c;
Tensor b_f, b_i, b_o, b_c;
Tensor alpha, beta_h, beta_i, b;

Tensor hidden_state_carried_dep;
Tensor cell_state_carried_dep;

vector<Tensor> y;
vector<Tensor> x;

// Assume * is overloaded as matmul, . is overloaded as Hadamard product
for (int i=0; i<seqlen; ++i) {
  Tensor affine_{f,i,o,c} = iW_{f,i,o,c} * x[t] + hW_{f,i,o,c} * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_{f,i,o,c};
  Tensor gates_{f,i,o,c} = x . alpha + beta_h . affine{f,i,o,c} + x . beta_i + b;
  y, hidden_state_carried_deps, cell_state_carried_dep = LSTMCell(gates, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep)
}
`

This is a perfectly reasonable representation in which a Funciton is *invoked* from a control structure body, whereas the body itself is a block, with access to values in the parent scope.

Equivalently, to explicitly capture live-in and live-out values in a function definition:

`
Tensor iW_f, iW_i, iW_o, iW_c;
Tensor hW_f, hW_i, hW_o, hW_c;
Tensor b_f, b_i, b_o, b_c;
Tensor alpha, beta_h, beta_i, b;

Tensor hidden_state_carried_dep;
Tensor cell_state_carried_dep;

vector<Tensor> y;
vector<Tensor> x;

for_loop_body(i_W, h_W, b, alpha, beta_h, beta_i, b) -> (y, hidden_state_carried_deps, cell_state_carried_deps) {
  Tensor affine_{f,i,o,c} = iW_{f,i,o,c} * x[t] + hW_{f,i,o,c} * hidden_state_carried_dep + b_{f,i,o,c};
  Tensor gates_{f,i,o,c} = x . alpha + beta_h . affine{f,i,o,c} + x . beta_i + b;
  y, hidden_state_carried_deps, cell_state_carried_dep = LSTMCell(gates, hidden_state_carried_dep, cell_state_carried_dep)
}
// Assume * is overloaded as matmul, . is overloaded as Hadamard product
for (int i=0; i<seqlen; ++i) for_loop_body(i_W, h_W, b, alpha, beta_h, beta_i, b)
`

Note that in all of these cases, having a well-defined semantics of lexical scope makes it so that a backend or any tools that wish to expressly enumerate the live-in values to a block can do so via analyzing the graph. The trade-off for strictly using Functions is increased complexity and size in the serialized model to simply represent information that is available implicitly.

This comment has been a summary of the considerations I've been making in choosing lexical scoping for the control flow ops, and assuming this Function proposal does not support behavior akin to lambdas, I argue that we should keep the Graph attribute as-is, or at least define a "block" semantics, distinct from the Function proposal.

@M00NSH0T Do we have any update for this part?

train_on_batch: I think this is what it's doing currently, but I'm not 100%. I'm concerned that if it's not using the Keras train_on_batch function for all updates to the neural network, then if you spend say a week training something with tons of historic data, then get a small amount of additional data and want to update the network, simply loading the neural net weights from the save file, training with the latest dataset, then saving the updated weights may weigh the new set much more than the far greater cache of original data. From my reading, it sounds like the keras train_on_batch function is better for this use case. It would be nice to build that in, if it isn't used already.

